  <rdfs:label rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Immune thrombocytopenia</rdfs:label>
  <ARI_Obsolete rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">false</ARI_Obsolete>
  <ARI_ID rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ARI:0001107</ARI_ID>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">438476003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2897005</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">13172003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">32273002</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">128091003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">128092005</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_DOID rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">8924</ARI_DOID>
  <ARI_UMLS rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">C0398650</ARI_UMLS>
  <ARI_ICD10 rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">D69.3</ARI_ICD10>
  <ARI_ICD10 rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">287.31</ARI_ICD10>
  <ARI_MESH rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">D016553</ARI_MESH>
  <ARI_NCI rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">C3446</ARI_NCI>
  <ARI_OMOP rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">4133983, 4230266, 318397, 4137430, 4103532, 4028065</ARI_OMOP>
  <ARI_DXCODE rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">13172003, 128092005, 2897005, 438476003, 32273002, 128091003</ARI_DXCODE>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Immune thrombocytopenia is a pair of autoimmune blood disorders that involves destruction of the normal blood clotting process. "Thrombocytopenia" simply means "low platelet count" and could be caused by many things. One symptom of these conditions is easy or excessive bruising and bleeding, so some names include the term "purpura", which means purple or red discolorations on the skin. The bleeding results from blood pooling under the skin because clotting is impaired.  Until scientists identified the autoimmune cause of the disease, it was called "idiopathic thrombocytopenia" because the cause was unknown, and until a cause of an individual's disease is known, that label might be used. 

In immune thrombocytopenia, the platlets are destroyed by the antibodies produced by the immune system. However, the tests for these antibodies are not precise, so other methods are used to confirm a diagnosis, including determining if other autoimmune diseases are present. Secondary autoimmune thrombocytopenia simply refers to immune thrombocytopenia triggered by another autoimmune disease or by a non-autoimmune disease (such as COVID-19). The treatments for secondary immune thrombocytopenia are usually determined by the underlying condition.

IIn autoimmune thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, sometimes called autoimmune TTP, autoantibodies attack ADAMTS13, an enzyme essential to regulating clot formation. The enzyme normally breaks down a protein called "ultra-large von Willebrand factor" (UL-vWF), and when that protein accumulates, platelets stick together, leading to blood clots. With the platelets stuck together, there are not enough platelets circulating in the bloodstream, which can lead to purpura (red or purple blotches on the skin). Although the symptoms of autoimmune TTP and immune thrombocytopenia are similar, the disease mechanism is very different.

Note that thrombotic thromocytopenic purpura, TTP, is a &lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;genetic&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt; disease that is caused by inherited genetic mutations in the ADAMTS13 gene that lead to the same symptoms as autoimmune TTP.  TTP is not autoimmune, and a genetic test to look for mutations in the gene that produces ADAMTS13 can be performed to rule out a genetic cause and lend support to a diagnosis of the autoimmune form of the disease.</rdfs:comment>
  <ARI_Synonym rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ATP</ARI_Synonym>
  <ARI_Synonym rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Autoimmune thrombocytopenic purpura</ARI_Synonym>
  <ARI_Synonym rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ITP</ARI_Synonym>
  <ARI_Synonym rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura</ARI_Synonym>
  <ARI_Synonym rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Immune-mediated thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (iTTP)</ARI_Synonym>
  <ARI_DefSource rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Segal 2006; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16869934/</ARI_DefSource>
  <ARI_Pubmed rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16869934/</ARI_Pubmed>
  <evidenceQuality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Antibody</evidenceQuality>
  <diseaseCategory rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Autoimmune</diseaseCategory>
  <ARI_Version rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2</ARI_Version>
  <ageRange rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Adult: 35-35 years</ageRange>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Platelet Disorder Support Association, PDSA | https://www.pdsa.org/</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Link to Cleveland Clinic | https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/5726-immune-thrombocytopenia</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Link to Healthline | https://www.healthline.com/health/idiopathic-thrombocytopenic-purpura-itp</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ITP Foundation | http://www.itpfoundation.org/</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Primary ITP - Not associated with another condition</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Secondary ATP - Associated with a non-autoimmune condition (e.g., H pylori, HIV)</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Secondary ITP - Associated with an autoimmune condition (e.g., lupus)</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_Author rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Raj Joshi | https://www.linkedin.com/in/rjoshi523/</ARI_Author>
