  <rdfs:label rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Pemphigus</rdfs:label>
  <ARI_Obsolete rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">false</ARI_Obsolete>
  <ARI_ID rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ARI:0001154</ARI_ID>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">46459009</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">402718003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">65172003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">35154004</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">36739006</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">49420001</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_SNOMED rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">200907003</ARI_SNOMED>
  <ARI_DOID rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">9182</ARI_DOID>
  <ARI_UMLS rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">C0030807</ARI_UMLS>
  <ARI_ICD10 rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">L10</ARI_ICD10>
  <ARI_ICD10 rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">694.4</ARI_ICD10>
  <ARI_MESH rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">D010392</ARI_MESH>
  <ARI_NCI rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">C34909</ARI_NCI>
  <ARI_OMOP rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">4262682, 4066821, 135338, 4279526, 4148690, 4291435, 4170723</ARI_OMOP>
  <ARI_DXCODE rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">46459009, 200907003, 65172003, 36739006, 35154004, 402718003, 49420001</ARI_DXCODE>
  <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Pemphigus includes a group of autoimmune diseases that cause blisters and sores in the mouth, skin, genitals, or any area that has mucous membranes. Normally, the immune system produces antibodies to fight off harmful invaders, such as viruses and bacteria. In pemphigus however, the body produces antibodies that damage cells of the skin, the junctions between them, and mucous membranes. Pemphigus vulgaris is the most common subtype of pemphigus.

Pemphigus can occur at any age, but it is most often seen in people who are middle-aged or older. It tends to be a long-lasting (chronic) condition, and some types can be life-threatening without treatment. Treatment with medication usually controls it.

Pemphigus is different from bullous pemphigoid, a blistering skin condition that affects older adults and may cause death to those in poor health. The main difference is microscopic: in pemphigus the skin cells are not able to stick to each other causing fluid to accumulate between them forming blisters;  bullous pemphigoid affects deeper layers of the skin, and the cells of the top layer of skin, the epidermis, cannot stick to the layer beneath it, the dermis, meaning they come off and fluid accumulates between the dermis and epidermis layer.</rdfs:comment>
  <ARI_DefSource rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Wertenteil 2019; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30892569/</ARI_DefSource>
  <ARI_Pubmed rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30892569/</ARI_Pubmed>
  <evidenceQuality rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Antibody</evidenceQuality>
  <diseaseCategory rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Autoimmune</diseaseCategory>
  <ARI_Version rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2</ARI_Version>
  <ageRange rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">50-60 years</ageRange>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Link to Healthline | https://www.healthline.com/health/pemphigus-vulgaris</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">The International Pemphigus &amp; Pemphigoid Foundation | http://www.pemphigus.org/</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_RefLink rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Link to Cleveland Clinic | https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/23033-pemphigus-vulgaris</ARI_RefLink>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Paraneoplastic Pemphigus - Linked to underlying malignancy.</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Pemphigus Vulgaris - Painful blisters on skin and mucous membranes.</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_ClinicalSubtype rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Pemphigus Foliaceus - Affects the skin, no mucosal involvement.</ARI_ClinicalSubtype>
  <ARI_Author rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Raj Joshi</ARI_Author>
  <ARI_AuthorDate rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2025-02</ARI_AuthorDate>
  <ARI_SurveyCode rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">PEM</ARI_SurveyCode>
  <ARI_ChangeLog rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">2026-06-15 10:37 | Importer | Imported from ARI core reports</ARI_ChangeLog>
</owl:NamedIndividual>

